title: Aust bonds higher amid weak US jobs data
text:
Fri, Jul 3, 2015, 10:38 AM AEST - Australia Markets close in 5 hrs 22 mins Aust bonds higher amid weak US jobs data AAP â€“ 1 hour 49 minutes ago Recommend Print 
The Australian bond market is stronger, tracking US trends amid weaker American jobs data. 
ANZ economists said US Treasuries rallied solidly overnight after the non-farm payrolls jobs report showed that the US had added 223,000 net new jobs in June, fewer than the 233,000 expected. 
The report also showed that average hourly earnings were flat in May, at $US24.95 ($A32.64), and up a modest 2.0 per cent year-on-year. That was lower than what most analysts had expected after the steady hiring gains of the past year. 
"While the data were mixed in June, on balance, it disappointed market expectations due to ongoing softness in average hourly earnings growth," they said. 
Markets interpreted the data as lessening the likelihood the Federal Reserve would begin hiking rates in September, ANZ economists said. 
At 0830 AEST on Friday, the September 2015 10-year bond futures contract was trading at 96.880 (implying a yield of 3.120 per cent), up from 96.845 (3.155 per cent) on Thursday. 
The September 2015 three-year bond futures contract was at 97.900 (2.100 per cent), up from 97.870 (2.130 per cent). 
KEY MOVEMENTS: 
* CGS 5.5pct Jan 2018, 2.054%, unchanged from Thursday 
* CGS 4.25pct April 2026, 3.189%, unchanged 
Sydney Futures Exchange prices: 
* September 2015 bill futures, 97.890 unchanged 
* December 2015 bill futures, 97.900, from 97.910 
(*Closes taken at 1630 AEST previous local session) 
Source: IRESS
